commit.message:
Response creation/update must receive a value for status (#2837)

# Description

**Warning:** review and merge PR
https://github.com/argilla-io/argilla/pull/2826 before this one.

This PR add changes to record responses so it must receive a value for
`status` when they are created or updated.

Related changes:
* Now when a response is created a `status` value is mandatory to be
used (previously it was optional with `submitted` as default).
  * This change affects frontend @keithCuniah
* Now response `values` is optional. You can create a response with
`status` to `discarded` without specifying a value for `values` field.
* This change affect database migrations. We need to rollback responses
table migration on `dev` environment and running it again after
deployment.

This PR affects the following endpoints:
* `GET  /datasets/{dataset_id}/records`
* `POST /datasets/{dataset_id}/records`
* `POST /records/{record_id}/responses`
* `PUT  /responses/{response_id}`

@keithCuniah feel free to add frontend changes if the PR is approved.

Closes #2762

---------

Co-authored-by: frascuchon <francis@argilla.io>

commit.message:
Use `/me` prefix for endpoints returning current user contextual response (#2826)

# Description

This PR include changes adding prefix `/me` to APIv1 endpoints that
build the response using current user as context. The behavior of these
endpoints has been changed too.

The include changes are:
* `GET` `/api/v1/datasets` changed to `GET` `/api/v1/me/datasets`
  *  The behavior of the endpoint didn't change.
* `GET` `/api/v1/datasets/{dataset_id}/records` changed to `GET`
`/api/v1/me/datasets/{dataset_id}/records`
  * The behavior for the endpoint returning record didn't change.
* The behavior including record responses changed and now it's only
including current user record responses (even if you are an admin).
* `GET` `/api/v1/records/{record_id}/responses` has been removed.
  * It wasn't being used by the frontend so I've deleted it for now.
 
@keithCuniah feel free to add the necessary frontend changes to this PR
replacing the use of the old endpoints to the new ones according to the
previous changes section. Take into account that endpoint
`/api/v1/me/datasets/{dataset_id}/records` is now only returning the
responses for the current user when `include=response` is used. (Prior
to this change the responses for all users where included when using
`include=response` and the user doing the request was an admin).

Closes #2823

---------

commit.message:
Add new endpoint to get current user dataset metrics (#2811)

# Description

This endpoint adds a new endpoint that will return the metrics for the
current user and for an specific dataset.

The new endpoint will be the first one for APIv1 where we are using the
prefix `/me` to notice that we are returning information in the context
of the current user doing the request.

The returned schema will be something like the following:
```json
{
        "records": {
            "count": 5,
        },
        "responses": {
            "count": 3,
            "submitted": 2,
            "discarded": 1,
        },
}
```

Associated issue: #2763

There was a bug on the backend detected by @keithCuniah when a dataset
with related questions is deleted giving a database error.

This was caused by SQLAlchemy default behavior trying to delete
explicitly relationships rows one by one.

This default behavior can be changed setting `passive_deletes=True` on
the defined model relationship. Meaning that the deletion will not be
done and it will be managed by the database (if available).

Add dataset fields (#2751)

# Description

This PR adds the following changes:
* Add a new database migration creating `fields` table.
* Add a SQLAlchemy `Field` model.
* Add a first endpoint to list fields for a specific dataset `GET
/api/v1/datasets/{dataset_id}/fields`

Notes:
* I have finally used `fields` instead of `field_settings` because the
naming started to feel strange when creating things like Pydantic
schemas. I'm open to suggestions for changing it.
* I didn't add an `Union` for `settings` on `Field` schema. It's because
right now it only has one type that is `text`. We can add the `Union`
and discriminator once that we have more than one type of field.

Closes #2750
